<subSubSection id="724EC9D03720096E5766642B20BE830B" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="195" pageId="1" pageNumber="194" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="ED6BF130E4C8430051EF5820524A6B7B" pageId="1" pageNumber="194">Diversity and distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="0811B6FE19E18BB698A5936B9A480449" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="195" pageId="1" pageNumber="194">
Fifteen species have been described from Brazil and one from Ecuador (
<bibRefCitation id="1A647A625C8BDBC2EE29A2FC02877F4C" author="Razowski, J" journalOrPublisher="SHILAP Revista de Lepidopterologia" pageId="11" pageNumber="204" pagination="385 - 393" title="Description of six Brazilian genera of Euliini and their species (Lepidoptera: Tortricidae)." volume="28" year="2000">Razowski and Becker 2000</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="B28ED19E55A0E85DD16D4A0C36DC0597" author="Razowski, J" journalOrPublisher="Polskie Pismo Entomologiczne" pageId="11" pageNumber="204" pagination="53 - 82" title="New species of Hynhamia Razowski and other genera close to Toreulia Razowski and Becker (Lepidoptera: Tortricidae)." url="https://doi.org/10.2478/v10200-011-0006-3" volume="80" year="2011">2011</bibRefCitation>
). To that we add one species 
<pageBreakToken id="110818646CCA127441F559F9AED8BE51" pageId="2" pageNumber="195" start="start">from</pageBreakToken>
Bolivia and another from Venezuela. Given the broad geographical and elevational range (from near sea level to ca. 2000 m), we suspect that 
<taxonomicName id="7A07787AD912A0F24BC47AFBE6677FA5" authority="Razowski &amp; Becker, 2000" authorityName="Razowski &amp; Becker" authorityYear="2000" class="Insecta" family="Tortricidae" genus="Brusqeulia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Brusqeulia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="195" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Brusqeulia</taxonomicName>
includes additional undiscovered species.
</paragraph>
